posts.name: Dan Nichols
posts.cooked:
Unless you are a Redux fan, itâ€™s probably not useful.

Again, most FRC CAN issues are with the wiring, and this kind of adapter is for recording data frames, not testing the electrical system.

Except for Redux (which posts their CAN message format here ), FRC suppliers donâ€™t publish the database files for deciding CAN traffic off the wire, for using an adapter like this. Youâ€™d just get a bunch of random bytes. The alternative is to use something like a Phoenix Tuner or Hoot logs, where the Phoenix black-box libraries decode the CAN traffic for you.

Funny story, it used to be pretty straightforward to reverse-engineer the CTRE CAN message format, until REV did it and made CTRE upset, who then promptly obfuscated the format. Much to the dismay of mentors from the automotive industry who are used to sniffing the CAN bus. Iâ€™d much rather use Vector CANalyzer than Phoenix Tuner to live view sensor data, but I canâ€™t.

As others have stated, most of the CAN problems are due to wiring issues that can be found using simpler tools and methods. Bad wiring would likely make this tool not detect anything. On very rare occasions, I have encountered dead CAN ports.

posts.name: Nathan Zhou
posts.cooked:
These CAN debugger are very useful if you are designing your own protocol. However when it comes to wiring issue, these things wonâ€™t help much. All you get when there is a wiring issue is nothing on the screen.

If you are experiencing wiring issue, the fastest method is unplug the battery and measure resistance between your two CAN wire. Normal resistance should be around 60 Ohm. If it is reading 120 Ohm, one termination resistor is missing (normal if you segment your CAN bus to pinpoint the issue). If it is 0 Ohm, it is shorted and if it is several kOhm, there is no termination on the line. Sometimes it is also necessary to check the resistance between each lines to power positive, power ground and chassis and see if anything is shorter to those.

Now in terms of use in FRC , if you want to see the exact data on CAN bus, you donâ€™t need to go out and buy one of these. If you have any REV CAN connected device, REV Hardware Client do have a built in CAN Data function which could let you see CAN frame. image 1004Ã—453 52 KB

NathanZhou:

Sometimes it is also necessary to check the resistance between each lines to power positive, power ground and chassis and see if anything is shorter to those.

We spent about an hour to find where a CAN wire was pressed against a sharp edge. The insulation was pierced, shorting it to the chassis rendering the CAN bus inoperable. The checks for opens, shorts and termination all indicated everything was OK. We only found the fault by bypassing sections of the CAN bus to isolate the fault to one run of wires then replacing the wires.

posts.name: Nathan Zhou
posts.cooked:
https://canable.io/updater/

CANAble have 2 types of firmware. SL- CAN and Candlelight.  To switch mode, you need to flash the firmware using the link above.

Candlelight firmware is better as it use USB protocol. To use it with python-can, you need the right firmware on your adapter using the updater and the right driver (libusb using zadig).

https://python-can.readthedocs.io/en/stable/interfaces/gs_usb.html#supported-platform

SL- CAN is the CAN over Serial mode. This mode had better compatibility but are slower. https://python-can.readthedocs.io/en/stable/interfaces/slcan.html

The form factor of this adapter varies. But as long as it say CANable, it is the same thing (software side).

And most importantly, your code with python-can needs to be setup correctly to talk to the right adapter at the right mode.

posts.name: billbo911
posts.cooked: We use a combination of software and a CAN map for diagnostics. When assembling the robot and finishing up the wiring,  make sure to create and end to end map of you bus(es). By viewing the bus from each end, via Phoenix Configuator on the Rio, a PDH or SparkMax etc., you should be able to see all devices on the bus. If you only see a partial list, typically, the failure is just after the last one.You see on the list. You can verify this by looking at the bus from the other end.And you should be able to see the remaining devices on the bus. Now that you know where the communication ends, you should be able to find where the error exists much more quickly.

posts.name: Ben Edwards
posts.cooked: I would also recommend an oscilloscope.  Not cheap, but hugely beneficial for seeing things no software will tell you. Look for clean edges, only small ringing after each edge, and for both CANH and CANL to move.  Dominant should be CANH near 3-4v and CANL near 0v, recessive should be both lines near 2v. You can see shorts to ground, shorts between the lines, improper termination, the effects if one line is open somewhere.  Quite useful for diagnostics beyond just bus off or data loss

posts.cooked: Are there any that you would recommend or do you have any tips for finding one that fits our needs?

posts.name: Ben Edwards
posts.cooked:
The primary characteristics of any oscilloscope are bandwidth and number of channels.  Secondary characteristics are sample rate (for modern digital scopes), user interface (knobs?  screen size?), trigger system complexity, measurements, protocol decoding, and accessory compatibility.  There are more things you can get into, generally youâ€™ll know if you need them.

A good rule of thumb for mixed signal diagnostics (like for CAN ) is that your scope bandwidth should be at least 10x your signal clock rate.  This allows you to see ringing, rise time issues, reflections and so forth without the scope lying to you.

For CAN FD, then, you need at least 100MHz of bandwidth (10Mbit data rate) and 2 channels.

Handheld scopes are nice for portability but their user interface is almost always awful.  If this is your first oscilloscope I would recommend a desktop â€œlunchboxâ€ form factor with knobs and buttons.  This is much easier to use, even though youâ€™re tied to a wall outlet.

The gold standards for oscilloscopes are from Tektronix, Teledyne-LeCroy, and Keysight.  Even for a 2 channel 100MHz scope they will run you thousands of dollars new.  The cost of a scope scales primarily with bandwidth & channels.   100 MHz from top tier manufacturers is around $2k,  200 MHz is about $4k, 1 GHz is about $12k.   They make faster ones.  If you need one of those later in life, youâ€™ll know it, and your company or lab will pay a LOT for it.  A 4 channel 10 GHz scope from Tektronix is $170k.  And then you pay again for 10 GHz probes, which all by themselves are north of $10k.

If youâ€™re willing to buy used, look on Ebay/FB Marketplace/local ham radio swap meet for a Tektronix TDS or TBS series scope, at least 2 channels, at least 100 MHz bandwidth.  The cheapest youâ€™ll find that are working will be about $200.  Youâ€™ll have to get probes as well, those will be $30-$50 for a pair of 100MHz probes.   For that money, a used Tektronix scope will be easier to use and probably last longer than anything new.

If you would prefer new, look on Digikey or Amazon for a 100 MHz 2 channel scope, benchtop type.  Hantek, Rigol, Siglent and GWInstek are okay brands.  Youâ€™ll pay about the same.  The user interface will be a little slower and clunkier.  I would not recommend anything cheaper than about $200 new, it will be utter junk and youâ€™ll hate it.

I use a portable OWON HDS2102 scope for CAN diagnostics at events, but the interface is terrible and itâ€™s not the best quality product.  We use the Tek TDS lunchbox scopes at work for basic stuff and have a couple of 1 GHz Teledyne-LeCroy scopes for heavy lifting.  But I do mostly embedded systems and motor controls, and so I donâ€™t need super high bandwidth.
